communications.subject: RE: Oklahoma Open Records Act Request #OCPD-3750-2025
communications.communication:
To whom it may concern: 
I am writing to formally appeal the denial of my request for records under the Oklahoma Open Records Act (“ORA”), which I submitted on 3/26/25. I respectfully request a written explanation detailing the specific grounds for the denial, including the precise subsections of the ORA that are being relied upon.
According to the ORA, “all records of public bodies and public officials shall be open to any person for inspection, copying, or mechanical reproduction during regular business hours…” unless specifically exempted by law. Your response cited the Oklahoma Open Records Act generally, referring to Sections 2, 5, 8, 14, and 20, but did not indicate what specific subsections within those provisions justify withholding the records I requested.
To ensure that the denial complies with the legal requirements of the ORA, and to allow me to properly evaluate the legitimacy of the denial, I ask that you provide the following:
The specific subsection(s) within ORA Sections 2, 5, 8, 14, and/or 20 that are being relied upon.


1. A description of how those subsections apply to the records I requested.


2. A list or description of the categories of records being withheld in whole or in part.


3. Whether any portion of the requested records is non-exempt and therefore subject to partial disclosure with redactions, as required by Oklahoma law.


The law is clear: ORA emphasizes transparency and access to public records as a matter of public policy. The Act requires that denials be specific and justified under the law; vague or categorical denials are inconsistent with both the letter and spirit of the Act.
I respectfully request a response to this appeal within a reasonable timeframe, ideally within seven (7) business days of receipt, so that I may determine my next steps.
If you require any clarification regarding my original request or this appeal, please let me know promptly.
Thank you.

communications.subject: Re: RE: Oklahoma Open Records Act Request #OCPD-3750-2025
communications.communication:

 RE: OCPD-3750-2025 / 2004-0051703 
  
 Per the Municipal Counselors Office on Apr. 2, 2025 @ 06:25 AM: "2004-0051703 provide open record version of incident report 000 and arrest report 013. Otherwise denied; ORA Sections 8 and 14." 
  
 After being unsure that your materials had been mailed out, I mailed out another copy of your materials on 05/27/2025. 
  
 In order to file an appeal: 
  
 The process is defined in Section 8 of the Open Records Act Law Enforcement Agency Records Available for Public Inspection, a link provided on the JustFOIA web page under “Open Records.” 
  
 Otherwise, the original decision was made by the Municipal Counselors Office. They can be contacted at 405-297-3830. Contact name is Orval Jones. Please provide your request number, OCPD-3750-2025, when you call so that they can reference your request. 
  
 Thank you.

communications.subject: New York Freedom of Information Law Request: New York SEA response
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the New York Freedom of Information Law, I hereby request the following records:

All documentation submitted to the U.S. Department of Education's Student Privacy Policy Office in response to the office's March 28, 2025, request for records such as "'reports, information on policies and procedures, annual notifications, training materials or other information necessary' to provide assurance that the SEA and their respective LEAs are complying with the provisions of FERPA and PPRA".

I have attached a copy of the SPPO's request letter for reference. The relevant section is found on the last page, under "Assurance of Compliance". The SPPO requested the documentation be submitted no later than April 30, 2025. If the New York Department of Education sent communications to the SPPO requesting an extension or declining to submit the documentation, I request a copy of said communications.

I also request that, if appropriate, fees be waived as I believe this request is in the public interest. The requested documents will be made available to the general public free of charge as part of the public information service at MuckRock.com, processed by a representative of the news media/press and is made in the process of news gathering and not for commercial usage.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 5 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Ileana Garnand

communications.subject: RE: New York Freedom of Information Law Request: New York SEA response
communications.communication:
Dear Ms. Garnand:

This is to acknowledge receipt of your Freedom of Information Law (FOIL) request for State Education Department (SED) records regarding New York SEA response.  The reference number for this request is FL-FL-25/543.   Please be advised that you will hear further from the Department by approximately June 5, 2025 as to whether your request will be granted or denied in whole or in part.

SED charges the statutorily permitted fees under FOIL. These include $.25 per page for photocopies or the actual cost of reproducing records requested under FOIL (Public Officers Law §87[1][b][iii]). Payment must be made to the NYS Education Department by check or money order. Do not send any payment until you are notified that your request is granted and informed of the charge for your request. If your request is granted, the records will be provided to you in the manner requested (i.e. hardcopy or electronic), or if not specified, in a reasonable manner selected by this office.

If your request is granted, and there is a fee, one of the following will happen:

1. If your request can be filled immediately, and the total photocopy or reproduction fee is under $25.00, staff will forward the requested records to you with a statement what you owe. Or:

2. If the reproduction fee or photocopy fee for your request is $25.00 or more, you will be advised of the page count (+100 pages) or other expenses and the fee(s) owed in advance of our providing the records. Upon receipt of payment, staff will photocopy or otherwise reproduce the requested records and transmit, as appropriate. Or:

3. If it will take time to locate and/or photocopy or otherwise reproduce the records you have requested, you will be given a date by which you will be provided with a page count and/or estimated cost to fulfil your request.

Please note, there is no provision in law or regulation requiring the waiver of a fee under FOIL.
Regards,
Records Access Officer

communications.subject: Freedom of Information Act Request: CENTCOM Iraq Coup/Uprising
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Freedom of Information Act, I hereby request the following records:

1) Any and all intelligence reports or analyses concerning the possibility of a military coup or popular uprising in Iraq prepared between April 1, 2002 and April 1, 2003.

2) Any and all contingency plans for responding to a military coup or popular uprising in Iraq prepared between April 1, 2002 and April 1, 2003.

3) Any and all intelligence analyses concerning the morale or cohesion of the Iraqi armed forces prepared between January 1, 2003 and April 1, 2003.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 20 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

David Lindsey

communications.subject: Wisconsin Open Records Act Request: Pandemic Unemployment Fraud Wisconsin Investigation
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Wisconsin Open Records Act, I hereby request the following records:

Subject: Freedom of Information Request for Unemployment Fraud Investigation Records

Dear Records Custodian,

I am submitting this Freedom of Information request under the Wisconsin Open Records Law (Wis. Stat. §§ 19.31–19.39) to obtain records related to an unemployment fraud investigation conducted by the Wisconsin Department of Workforce Development (DWD), specifically involving Adjudicator #5139 (Mark, last name withheld) and Investigator Christine Francke.

I am seeking the following records:





The current status of the unemployment fraud investigation referenced in communications with Christine Francke on February 21, 2025, and May 16, 2025.



Copies of correspondence notes, internal memos, or reports generated by or involving Adjudicator #5139 (Mark) and Christine Francke related to the investigation, including any notes from a phone call on or about February 20, 2025, with Alexander Lennon regarding evidence collection.



Records acknowledging or referencing the receipt and review of evidence I submitted, including:





Documents emailed on February 21, 2025, detailing bicycle sales and Venmo transactions for the period referenced in the investigation.



Evidence submitted on May 16, 2025, including the IPV Hearing Decision (EXHIBIT D 2024-12-20), redacted BMO account statements, US Bank account proof, E-Trade account details, a forensic accountant’s tally of deposits (Tanya BMO Working_01March2024.xlsx), a letter of engagement from Anish Neupane, a memo from private investigator Jeff Janda, and related correspondence.



A police report (EXHIBIT B 2025-05-13 WPD Report 2025-124662 wFollowUp) emailed on May 21, 2025, confirming the individual’s self-identification in connection with the IPV report and PUA fraud investigation.



Any correspondence between DWD staff (including Christine Francke or Adjudicator #5139) and the individual under investigation, Angie Dempewolfe, regarding the PUA fraud or IPV FoodShare fraud investigation, to the extent permitted by law.



Any determinations, findings, or decisions related to the PUA overpayment or fraud allegations, redacted as necessary to comply with confidentiality requirements.

I understand that certain records may be subject to confidentiality restrictions under state or federal law, including those protecting personal information or ongoing investigations. I request that any non-exempt portions of the records be released, with appropriate redactions applied to comply with privacy laws. If any records are withheld, please provide a written explanation citing the specific statutory exemptions.

To facilitate processing, my contact information is: Alexander Lennon Email: alennon727@gmail.com Phone: 608-214-6492

Please confirm receipt of this request and provide an estimated timeline for response. If there are any fees associated with this request, please notify me in advance. I prefer to receive the records electronically via email, if possible.

Thank you for your attention to this matter.

Sincerely, Alexander Lennon

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 10 business days.

Sincerely,

Alexander Lennon

communications.subject: RE: Wisconsin Open Records Act Request: Pandemic Unemployment Fraud Wisconsin Investigation
communications.communication:
Good afternoon,

This email is in response to your May 29, 2025 public records request for the following records:

"I am submitting this Freedom of Information request under the Wisconsin Open Records Law (Wis. Stat. §§ 19.31–19.39) to obtain records related to an unemployment fraud investigation conducted by the Wisconsin Department of Workforce Development (DWD), specifically involving Adjudicator #5139 (Mark, last name withheld) and Investigator Christine Francke.

I am seeking the following records:

The current status of the unemployment fraud investigation referenced in communications with Christine Francke on February 21, 2025, and May 16, 2025.

Copies of correspondence notes, internal memos, or reports generated by or involving
Adjudicator #5139 (Mark) and Christine Francke related to the investigation, including any notes from a phone call on or about February 20, 2025, with Alexander Lennon regarding evidence collection.

Records acknowledging or referencing the receipt and review of evidence I submitted, including:

Documents emailed on February 21, 2025, detailing bicycle sales and Venmo transactions for the period referenced in the investigation.

Evidence submitted on May 16, 2025, including the IPV Hearing Decision (EXHIBIT D 2024-12-20), redacted BMO account statements, US Bank account proof, E-Trade account details, a forensic accountant’s tally of deposits (Tanya BMO Working_01March2024.xlsx), a letter of engagement from Anish Neupane, a memo from private investigator Jeff Janda, and related correspondence.

A police report (EXHIBIT B 2025-05-13 WPD Report 2025-124662 wFollowUp) emailed on May 21, 2025, confirming the individual’s self-identification in connection with the IPV report and PUA fraud investigation.

Any correspondence between DWD staff (including Christine Francke or Adjudicator #5139) and the individual under investigation, Angie Dempewolfe, regarding the PUA fraud or IPV FoodShare fraud investigation, to the extent permitted by law.

Any determinations, findings, or decisions related to the PUA overpayment or fraud allegations, redacted as necessary to comply with confidentiality requirements."

For the item of your request requesting "Records acknowledging or referencing the receipt and review of evidence I submitted," the responsive records have been attached to this message. Please note that the Department would have normally redacted your personal email address from these records. However, since you are the individual who submitted this personally identifiable information when you submitted the information to the Department's Unemployment Insurance Division, these records are being provided without redaction.

For the remaining items of your request:

Information Identifying Individual Unemployment Insurance Claimants: The Department considers information regarding whether an individual is receiving, has received, or has applied for unemployment insurance to be confidential. See 20 CFR §§ 603.4, 603.5; Wis. Stat. § 108.14(7)(a); and Wis. Admin. Code § DWD 149.02. Therefore, the Department has withheld documents that identify individuals who are receiving, have received, or have applied for unemployment insurance.

Pursuant to Wis. Stat. § 19.35(4)(b), to the extent this is a denial, this determination is subject to review by mandamus under Wis. Stat. § 19.37(1) or upon application to a district attorney or the Attorney General.

Thank you,

Open Records
State of Wisconsin | Department of Workforce Development
OpenRecords@dwd.wisconsin.gov<mailto:OpenRecords@dwd.wisconsin.gov>
Tel: (608) 261-6216
